page {
  background-color: #fff;
  --primary-color: #FFDA44; /* Changed to Yellow */
  --primary-btn-color: #4A90E2; /* Keep button blue as per screenshot? No, user said "ba主体颜色换位我目前的黄色", but screenshot has blue button. User said "except for the main color changed to my current yellow". 
  Wait, "ba主体颜色换位我目前的黄色" -> "change main color to my current yellow".
  In the screenshot, the tabs are blue, the button is blue.
  If I change main color to yellow:
  - Tabs active color -> Yellow
  - Button color -> Yellow (or keep blue? usually "main color" implies the primary action color too).
  However, standard yellow buttons with white text might have contrast issues if the yellow is too light.
  The user's yellow is #FFDA44.
  Let's check the screenshot again.
  Screenshot: Tabs blue text, blue underline. Button blue background.
  User instruction: "change main color to my current yellow".
  So I should probably make the tabs yellow and the button yellow.
  The button text color might need to be black if yellow is light.
  Let's use the variable --brand-yellow from app.wxss which is #FFDA44.
  */
}

.container {
  padding-bottom: 40rpx;
}

/* Tabs */
.tabs {
  display: flex;
  background: #fff;
  border-bottom: 1rpx solid #eee;
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 100;
}

.tab-item {
  flex: 1;
  text-align: center;
  padding: 24rpx 0;
  font-size: 30rpx;
  color: #333;
  position: relative;
}

.tab-item.active {
  color: #333; /* Usually active tab is highlighted. With yellow, maybe just bold? or yellow text? Yellow text on white might be hard to read. Let's use bold and the line. */
  font-weight: 600;
}

.tab-line {
  position: absolute;
  bottom: 0;
  left: 50%;
  transform: translateX(-50%);
  width: 40rpx;
  height: 6rpx;
  background: var(--brand-yellow, #FFDA44);
  border-radius: 4rpx;
}

/* Form */
.content {
  padding: 0 32rpx;
}

.form-group {
  margin-top: 20rpx;
}

.form-item {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: space-between;
  align-items: center;
  padding: 32rpx 0;
  border-bottom: 1rpx solid #f5f5f5;
  font-size: 30rpx;
}

.label {
  color: #333;
  font-weight: 500;
}

.input-wrapper {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
}

input {
  text-align: right;
  font-size: 30rpx;
  color: #333;
  width: 200rpx;
}

.unit {
  margin-left: 10rpx;
  color: #666;
}

.picker {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  color: #333;
}

.arrow {
  margin-left: 10rpx;
  color: #ccc;
  font-size: 32rpx;
}

/* Radio Group */
.radio-group {
  display: flex;
  gap: 30rpx;
}

.radio {
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  font-size: 28rpx;
  color: #333;
}

radio {
  transform: scale(0.8);
}

/* LPR Info */
.lpr-info {
  background: #F5F7FA;
  padding: 20rpx;
  border-radius: 8rpx;
  display: flex;
  align-items: center;
  margin: 20rpx 0;
  font-size: 24rpx;
}

.lpr-tag {
  background: #4A90E2; /* Keep this blue as it's likely an info tag? Or change to yellow? Screenshot has blue tag. I'll keep it blue for contrast or use a darker yellow. */
  color: #fff;
  padding: 2rpx 8rpx;
  border-radius: 4rpx;
  font-size: 20rpx;
  margin-right: 12rpx;
}

.lpr-text {
  flex: 1;
  color: #666;
}

.lpr-link {
  color: #4A90E2;
}

/* Divider */
.divider {
  height: 20rpx;
  background: #f8f8f8;
  margin: 0 -32rpx;
}

/* Button */
.btn-area {
  margin-top: 60rpx;
}

.btn-calculate {
  background: #4A90E2; /* Screenshot is blue. User said change main color to yellow. */
  /* If I change to yellow: */
  background: var(--brand-yellow, #FFDA44);
  color: #333; /* Black text on yellow */
  border-radius: 8rpx;
  font-size: 32rpx;
  font-weight: 600;
  padding: 20rpx 0;
}

.btn-calculate::after {
  border: none;
}

.footer-links {
  display: flex;
  justify-content: center;
  align-items: center;
  margin-top: 40rpx;
  font-size: 26rpx;
  color: #999;
}

.separator {
  margin: 0 20rpx;
  color: #ddd;
}
